{"title_page": "Richard K. Morgan", "text_new": "{{Use British English |date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates |date=December 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Richard K. Morgan\n| image       = Richard Morgan 270408.jpg\n| imagesize   = 200px\n| caption     = Morgan in [[Zagreb]] at [[SFeraKon]], 2008\n| birth_date  =  {{b-da|24 September 1965}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], England\n| occupation  = Writer\n| residence  = [[Saxlingham Nethergate]], [[Norfolk]]\n| parents    = John Morgan (father), Margaret Morgan (mother)\n| spouse     = Virginia Gema Cottinelli-Herrero\n| children   = Daniel Morgan Cottinelli\n| genre       = [[Hardboiled]], [[postcyberpunk]], [[Science fiction]], [[fantasy]]\n| signature   =\n| website     = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n'''Richard Kingsley Morgan''', (born 24 September 1965) is a British [[science fiction]] and [[fantasy]] author.\n\nMorgan's books are generally set in a post-[[extropianism|extropianist]] [[dystopia]]n world. Morgan described his \"takeaway\" of one of his books as: {{cquote|Society is, always has been and always will be a structure for the exploitation and oppression of the majority through systems of political force dictated by an \u00e9lite, enforced by thugs, uniformed or not, and upheld by a wilful ignorance and stupidity on the part of the majority whom the system oppresses.<ref>Morgan discussing his \"take away\" of his novel ''[[Altered Carbon]]'', in  [http://www.saxonbullock.com/2014/04/never-mind-the-cyberpunks-an-interview-with-richard-morgan-2002/ \"Never Mind the Cyberpunks: An Interview with Richard Morgan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426082539/http://www.saxonbullock.com/2014/04/never-mind-the-cyberpunks-an-interview-with-richard-morgan-2002/ |date=26 April 2016 }}, SaxonBullock.com.  Originally published online at SlateMagazine.co.uk, 2002.</ref>}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBorn in [[London]], and brought up in the village of [[Hethersett]], near [[Norwich]], Morgan studied history at [[Queens' College, Cambridge]]. After graduating he started [[teaching English as a foreign language|teaching English]] in order to travel the world. After 14 years and a post at the [[University of Strathclyde]], his first novel was published and he became a full-time writer. He lived in [[Glasgow]] until 2015, when he moved to [[Saxlingham Nethergate]] with his wife Virginia and their son Daniel.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.edp24.co.uk/going-out/altered-carbon-author-richard-morgan-on-new-netflix-adaptation-1-5403512 |title=Meet the Norfolk author behind Netflix's biggest new series |date=18 February 2018 |work=Eastern Daily Press}}</ref>\n\n==Literary career==\nIn 2002, Morgan's first novel ''[[Altered Carbon]]'' was published, combining elements of \"[[cyberpunk]]\" and [[hardboiled]] [[detective fiction]] and featuring the [[antihero]] [[Takeshi Kovacs]]. The film rights for the book sold for a reported figure of $1,000,000 to [[film producer]] [[Joel Silver]], enabling Morgan to become a full-time writer. In 2003 the U.S. edition received the [[Philip K. Dick Award#2003|Philip K. Dick Award]].\n\nIn 2003, ''[[Broken Angels (novel)|Broken Angels]]'' was published, the sequel to ''Altered Carbon'', again featuring Takeshi Kovacs and blending science fiction and [[war novel|war fiction]] in a similar way to his cross-[[genre]] d\u00e9but.\n\n''[[Market Forces]]'', Morgan's first non-Kovacs novel, is set in the not-too-distant future. It was originally written as a short story, then as a screenplay (both unpublished). After the success of his first two works, it was released as a novel and optioned as a film.\n\nMorgan's third, and he has stated final,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itconversations.com/shows/detail1899.html |title=Interview with Richard Morgan |date=16 August 2005 |work=IT Conversations }}</ref> Kovacs novel ''[[Woken Furies]]'' was released in the UK in March 2005 and in the U.S. in September 2005.\n\nMorgan wrote two six issue miniseries for [[Marvel Comics]] under the [[Marvel Knights]] imprint. His first story, ''[[Black Widow (Natalia Romanova)|Black Widow]]: Homecoming'' published monthly in 2004 was followed by a second, ''Black Widow: The Things They Say About Her'' published monthly in 2005; both are available in collected editions. According to Morgan's official website the series was \"an artefact of limited appeal\" and is unlikely to be continued, although he has other comic projects in development.\n\n''[[Black Man]]'' was released in May 2007 in the UK and in June 2007 in the United States (as ''Thirteen'' or ''Th1rte3n''). According to the author, the book is about the constraints of physicality and the fact that people are locked into who they are. These are things he could not deal with in the Kovacs universe, because for Kovacs and people like him mortality is avoidable: they just skip into a new body.<ref>{{cite web |author=[[Moira Gunn]] |title=Tech Nation |url=http://www.yourmomsbasement.com/archives/2005/08/interview_with_2.html |publisher=Your Mom's Basement |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090804051247/http://www.yourmomsbasement.com/archives/2005/08/interview_with_2.html |archivedate=4 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The novel won the 2008 [[Arthur C. Clarke Award]].\n\nMorgan wrote a fantasy trilogy with a [[gay]] protagonist, ''A Land Fit for Heroes'', the first volume of which has the title ''[[The Steel Remains]]'' and was published in August 2008 in the UK<ref>{{cite web |title=The Steel Remains |url=http://www.richardkmorgan.com/novels/the-steel-remains/ |publisher=Richard Morgan's website |access-date=8 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110917073655/http://www.richardkmorgan.com/novels/the-steel-remains/ |archive-date=17 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and on 20 January 2009 in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Steel-Remains-Richard-K-Morgan/dp/0345493036/ |title=The Steel Remains (Hardcover) |publisher=[[Amazon.com]] |access-date=10 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719214712/https://www.amazon.com/Steel-Remains-Richard-K-Morgan/dp/0345493036 |archive-date=19 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second volume, titled ''[[The Cold Commands]]'' was published in 2011. The third book in the series is called ''[[The Dark Defiles]]'' and was published on 17 August 2014.<ref name=\"defiles\">{{cite web |url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13486172-the-dark-defiles |title=Richard K Morgan - The Dark Defiles early cover art revealed |publisher=[[Gollancz Limited]] |access-date=28 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121224004620/http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13486172-the-dark-defiles |archive-date=24 December 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLiber Primus Games is creating a gamebook series based on the ''A Land Fit For Heroes'' trilogy. The first game was published for Android, Apple and Amazon Kindle Fire devices on 4 November 2015.\n\nIn 2008, he worked with [[Starbreeze]] as a writer for ''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'', the 2012 re-imagining of the [[Syndicate (video game)|1992 original]].<ref>{{cite news |author=[[Michael Plant]] |title=Interview: Richard Morgan on rebooting Syndicate |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/interview-richard-morgan-on-rebooting-syndicate-7581320.html |publisher=[[The Independent]] |location=London |date=22 March 2012 |access-date=10 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201030337/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/interview-richard-morgan-on-rebooting-syndicate-7581320.html |archive-date=1 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, Morgan worked with [[Electronic Arts]] and [[Crytek]] as lead writer for their 2011 video game, ''[[Crysis 2]]''.\n\nIn October 2018, Morgan's science fiction novel, ''[[Thin Air (2018 novel)|Thin Air]]'' was published in the UK by Gollancz.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Morgan |first1=Richard |title=Thin Air |date=2018 |publisher=Gollancz |location=U.K. |isbn=9780575075146}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview before the launch of ''Thin Air'', Morgan described a common feature of his works:\n\n{{Quote|There is a central conceit that I keep\u2009\u2014\u2009not consciously, I swear!\u2009\u2014\u2009returning to in my work. It takes different metaphorical guises, but at root it\u2019s always the same sense of something grand and worthwhile being abandoned by vicious and stupid men in favour of short-term profit and tribal hegemony. You see it in the regressive politics of the Protectorate in the Kovacs novels, the way both the Yhelteth Empire and the\u2009\u2014\u2009so-called\u2009\u2014\u2009Free Cities fail their duty as civilisations in ''A Land Fit for Heroes''. So also with ''Thin Air''\u2009\u2014\u2009the landscape is littered with the markers of a retreat from the grand scheme of terraforming and building a home for humanity on Mars, in favour of an ultraprofitable corporate stasis and an ongoing lie of highly emotive intangibles sold to the general populace in lieu of actual progress.<ref name=\"H\u00e9lice interview\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.revistahelice.com/revista_textos/n_25/Helice.%202019%20Oto%C3%B1o-Invierno%20MARTIAN%20POLITICS%20AND%20THE%20HARD-BOILED%20ANTI-HERO.pdf |title=Martian Politics and the Hard-Boiled Anti-Hero: Richard Morgan\u2019s ''Thin Air'' |author=Sara Mart\u00edn Alegre |year=2018 |journal=Revista H\u00e9lice |volume=4 |issue=11 |pages=84\u201395 |format=PDF |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204065914/https://www.revistahelice.com/revista_textos/n_25/Helice.%202019%20Oto%C3%B1o-Invierno%20MARTIAN%20POLITICS%20AND%20THE%20HARD-BOILED%20ANTI-HERO.pdf |archivedate=4 February 2019 |access-date=3 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n\nA graphic novel titled ''Altered Carbon: Download Blues'', which continues to follow the character Takeshi Kovacs, was released in July 2019.\n\nAn animated feature entitled ''Altered Carbon: Resleeved'' was released in 2020 on Netflix.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Takeshi Kovacs novels===\n* ''[[Altered Carbon]]'' ([[2002 in literature|2002]]) {{ISBN|0-575-07390-X}}\n* ''[[Broken Angels (novel)|Broken Angels]]'' ([[2003 in literature|2003]]) {{ISBN|0-575-07550-3}}\n* ''[[Woken Furies]]'' ([[2005 in literature|2005]]) {{ISBN|0-575-07325-X}}\n* ''[[Altered Carbon: Download Blues]]'' ([[2019 in literature|2019]]) {{ISBN|978-1524109677}}\n\n===''A Land Fit For Heroes''===\n* ''[[The Steel Remains]]'' (2008) {{ISBN|0-575-07792-1}}\n* ''[[The Cold Commands]]'' (2011) {{ISBN|0-575-07793-X}}\n* ''[[The Dark Defiles]]'' (2014) {{ISBN|0575088605}}<ref name=\"defiles\" />\n\n=== Black Man novels ===\n* ''[[Black Man]]'' ([[2007 in literature|2007]]) {{ISBN|0-575-07513-9}} (known as ''Thirteen'' or ''Th1rte3n'' in the United States {{ISBN|0-345-48525-4}})\n* ''[[Thin Air (2018 novel)|Thin Air]]'' (2018) {{ISBN|9780575075146}}\n\n===Other novels===\n* ''[[Market Forces]]'' ([[2004 in literature|2004]]) {{ISBN|0-575-07584-8}}\n\n===Graphic novels===\n* ''[[Black Widow (Natalia Romanova)|Black Widow: Homecoming]]'' ([[2005 in literature|2005]]) {{ISBN|0-7851-1493-9}}\n* ''[[Black Widow (Natalia Romanova)|Black Widow: The Things They Say About Her]]'' ([[2006 in literature|2006]]) {{ISBN|0-7851-1768-7}}\n*''[[Altered Carbon: Download Blues]]'' ([[2019 in literature|2019]]) {{ISBN|978-1524109677}}\n\n===Video games===\n* ''[[Crysis 2]]'' ([[2011 in video gaming|2011]])\n* ''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'' ([[2012 in video gaming|2012]])\n* ''A Land Fit For Heroes'' (2015)\n\n===Music===\n* \"Woken Furies\" from the album ''Dark All Day'' by [[Gunship (band)|Gunship]] (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Richard Morgan}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{isfdb name|name=Richard Morgan}}\n\n===Interviews===\n* [http://www.scifi.com/sfw/issue373/interview.html ''Science Fiction Weekly'' interview]\n* [http://www.jivemagazine.com/article.php?pid=3718 ''JIVE Magazine'' interview]\n* [http://www.infinityplus.co.uk/nonfiction/intrm.htm ''InfinityPlus'' interview]\n* [http://www.yourmomsbasement.com/archives/2005/08/richard_morgan_1.html Morgan Week interviews and reviews]\n* [http://clarkesworldmagazine.com/morgan_interview/ Interview ''Clarkesworld Magazine'' 2008-9]\n* [http://www.scifidimensions.com/main/2008/08/15/podcast-13-richard-k-morgan/ Interview on the SciFiDimensions Podcast]\n\n===Scandal===\nMorgan was banned from Mastodon for being a transphobe. This section will be deleted within a day because wikipedia itself is transphobic. They will silence trans people by ignoring evidence, dismiss them as vandals, and pretend to be neutral when really they're just transphobic. They have repeatedly misgendered the Roman Empress Elagabalus, and refused to remove someone's deadname even when their victims explicitly asked them to. They devote their time in dismissing and erasing evidence of transphobia instead of looking into it, because in truth they hate trans people and are glad that trans people are being, raped, murdered, and having their rights stripped. Even if some trans people are children. Wikibros will keep finding shit reasons like \"improper use of humor\" to silence people, because they can't be bothered to put in any effort to help trans people at all and would rather help to prosecute them. It matters not to us. We will do this again, again, and again, until they obtain the basic decency to recognize rudimentary facts. They cannot stop us. We're the Durruti Column. We do not forgive. We do not forget. Expect us.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Carol Emshwiller]]<br/>for ''[[The Mount (novel)|The Mount]]'' }}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Philip K. Dick Award]] |years=2003<br/>'''for ''[[Altered Carbon]]'' ''' }}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Gwyneth Jones (novelist)|Gwyneth Jones]]<br/>for ''[[Life (novel)|Life]]'' }}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Jack McDevitt]]<br/>for ''[[Omega]]'' }}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[John W. Campbell Memorial Award for Best Science Fiction Novel|John W. Campbell Memorial Award<br/>for Best Science Fiction Novel]] |years=2005<br/>'''for ''[[Market Forces]]'' ''' }}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Robert J. Sawyer]]<br/>for ''[[Mindscan]]'' }}\n{{s-bef |before=[[M. John Harrison]]<br/>for ''[[Nova Swing]]'' }}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Arthur C. Clarke Award]] |years=2008<br/>'''for ''[[Black Man]]'' ''' }}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Ian R. MacLeod]]<br/>for ''[[Ian R. MacLeod|Song of Time]]'' }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Richard K. Morgan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morgan, Richard K.}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cyberpunk writers]]\n[[Category:Postmodern writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:People from Hethersett]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Strathclyde]]\n[[Category:English male novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English |date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates |date=December 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Richard K. Morgan\n| image       = Richard Morgan 270408.jpg\n| imagesize   = 200px\n| caption     = Morgan in [[Zagreb]] at [[SFeraKon]], 2008\n| birth_date  =  {{b-da|24 September 1965}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], England\n| occupation  = Writer\n| residence  = [[Saxlingham Nethergate]], [[Norfolk]]\n| parents    = John Morgan (father), Margaret Morgan (mother)\n| spouse     = Virginia Gema Cottinelli-Herrero\n| children   = Daniel Morgan Cottinelli\n| genre       = [[Hardboiled]], [[postcyberpunk]], [[Science fiction]], [[fantasy]]\n| signature   =\n| website     = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n'''Richard Kingsley Morgan''', (born 24 September 1965) is a British [[science fiction]] and [[fantasy]] author.\n\nMorgan's books are generally set in a post-[[extropianism|extropianist]] [[dystopia]]n world. Morgan described his \"takeaway\" of one of his books as: {{cquote|Society is, always has been and always will be a structure for the exploitation and oppression of the majority through systems of political force dictated by an \u00e9lite, enforced by thugs, uniformed or not, and upheld by a wilful ignorance and stupidity on the part of the majority whom the system oppresses.<ref>Morgan discussing his \"take away\" of his novel ''[[Altered Carbon]]'', in  [http://www.saxonbullock.com/2014/04/never-mind-the-cyberpunks-an-interview-with-richard-morgan-2002/ \"Never Mind the Cyberpunks: An Interview with Richard Morgan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426082539/http://www.saxonbullock.com/2014/04/never-mind-the-cyberpunks-an-interview-with-richard-morgan-2002/ |date=26 April 2016 }}, SaxonBullock.com.  Originally published online at SlateMagazine.co.uk, 2002.</ref>}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBorn in [[London]], and brought up in the village of [[Hethersett]], near [[Norwich]], Morgan studied history at [[Queens' College, Cambridge]]. After graduating he started [[teaching English as a foreign language|teaching English]] in order to travel the world. After 14 years and a post at the [[University of Strathclyde]], his first novel was published and he became a full-time writer. He lived in [[Glasgow]] until 2015, when he moved to [[Saxlingham Nethergate]] with his wife Virginia and their son Daniel.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.edp24.co.uk/going-out/altered-carbon-author-richard-morgan-on-new-netflix-adaptation-1-5403512 |title=Meet the Norfolk author behind Netflix's biggest new series |date=18 February 2018 |work=Eastern Daily Press}}</ref>\n\n==Literary career==\nIn 2002, Morgan's first novel ''[[Altered Carbon]]'' was published, combining elements of \"[[cyberpunk]]\" and [[hardboiled]] [[detective fiction]] and featuring the [[antihero]] [[Takeshi Kovacs]]. The film rights for the book sold for a reported figure of $1,000,000 to [[film producer]] [[Joel Silver]], enabling Morgan to become a full-time writer. In 2003 the U.S. edition received the [[Philip K. Dick Award#2003|Philip K. Dick Award]].\n\nIn 2003, ''[[Broken Angels (novel)|Broken Angels]]'' was published, the sequel to ''Altered Carbon'', again featuring Takeshi Kovacs and blending science fiction and [[war novel|war fiction]] in a similar way to his cross-[[genre]] d\u00e9but.\n\n''[[Market Forces]]'', Morgan's first non-Kovacs novel, is set in the not-too-distant future. It was originally written as a short story, then as a screenplay (both unpublished). After the success of his first two works, it was released as a novel and optioned as a film.\n\nMorgan's third, and he has stated final,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itconversations.com/shows/detail1899.html |title=Interview with Richard Morgan |date=16 August 2005 |work=IT Conversations }}</ref> Kovacs novel ''[[Woken Furies]]'' was released in the UK in March 2005 and in the U.S. in September 2005.\n\nMorgan wrote two six issue miniseries for [[Marvel Comics]] under the [[Marvel Knights]] imprint. His first story, ''[[Black Widow (Natalia Romanova)|Black Widow]]: Homecoming'' published monthly in 2004 was followed by a second, ''Black Widow: The Things They Say About Her'' published monthly in 2005; both are available in collected editions. According to Morgan's official website the series was \"an artefact of limited appeal\" and is unlikely to be continued, although he has other comic projects in development.\n\n''[[Black Man]]'' was released in May 2007 in the UK and in June 2007 in the United States (as ''Thirteen'' or ''Th1rte3n''). According to the author, the book is about the constraints of physicality and the fact that people are locked into who they are. These are things he could not deal with in the Kovacs universe, because for Kovacs and people like him mortality is avoidable: they just skip into a new body.<ref>{{cite web |author=[[Moira Gunn]] |title=Tech Nation |url=http://www.yourmomsbasement.com/archives/2005/08/interview_with_2.html |publisher=Your Mom's Basement |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090804051247/http://www.yourmomsbasement.com/archives/2005/08/interview_with_2.html |archivedate=4 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The novel won the 2008 [[Arthur C. Clarke Award]].\n\nMorgan wrote a fantasy trilogy with a [[gay]] protagonist, ''A Land Fit for Heroes'', the first volume of which has the title ''[[The Steel Remains]]'' and was published in August 2008 in the UK<ref>{{cite web |title=The Steel Remains |url=http://www.richardkmorgan.com/novels/the-steel-remains/ |publisher=Richard Morgan's website |access-date=8 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110917073655/http://www.richardkmorgan.com/novels/the-steel-remains/ |archive-date=17 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and on 20 January 2009 in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Steel-Remains-Richard-K-Morgan/dp/0345493036/ |title=The Steel Remains (Hardcover) |publisher=[[Amazon.com]] |access-date=10 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719214712/https://www.amazon.com/Steel-Remains-Richard-K-Morgan/dp/0345493036 |archive-date=19 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second volume, titled ''[[The Cold Commands]]'' was published in 2011. The third book in the series is called ''[[The Dark Defiles]]'' and was published on 17 August 2014.<ref name=\"defiles\">{{cite web |url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13486172-the-dark-defiles |title=Richard K Morgan - The Dark Defiles early cover art revealed |publisher=[[Gollancz Limited]] |access-date=28 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121224004620/http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13486172-the-dark-defiles |archive-date=24 December 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLiber Primus Games is creating a gamebook series based on the ''A Land Fit For Heroes'' trilogy. The first game was published for Android, Apple and Amazon Kindle Fire devices on 4 November 2015.\n\nIn 2008, he worked with [[Starbreeze]] as a writer for ''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'', the 2012 re-imagining of the [[Syndicate (video game)|1992 original]].<ref>{{cite news |author=[[Michael Plant]] |title=Interview: Richard Morgan on rebooting Syndicate |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/interview-richard-morgan-on-rebooting-syndicate-7581320.html |publisher=[[The Independent]] |location=London |date=22 March 2012 |access-date=10 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201030337/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/interview-richard-morgan-on-rebooting-syndicate-7581320.html |archive-date=1 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, Morgan worked with [[Electronic Arts]] and [[Crytek]] as lead writer for their 2011 video game, ''[[Crysis 2]]''.\n\nIn October 2018, Morgan's science fiction novel, ''[[Thin Air (2018 novel)|Thin Air]]'' was published in the UK by Gollancz.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Morgan |first1=Richard |title=Thin Air |date=2018 |publisher=Gollancz |location=U.K. |isbn=9780575075146}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview before the launch of ''Thin Air'', Morgan described a common feature of his works:\n\n{{Quote|There is a central conceit that I keep\u2009\u2014\u2009not consciously, I swear!\u2009\u2014\u2009returning to in my work. It takes different metaphorical guises, but at root it\u2019s always the same sense of something grand and worthwhile being abandoned by vicious and stupid men in favour of short-term profit and tribal hegemony. You see it in the regressive politics of the Protectorate in the Kovacs novels, the way both the Yhelteth Empire and the\u2009\u2014\u2009so-called\u2009\u2014\u2009Free Cities fail their duty as civilisations in ''A Land Fit for Heroes''. So also with ''Thin Air''\u2009\u2014\u2009the landscape is littered with the markers of a retreat from the grand scheme of terraforming and building a home for humanity on Mars, in favour of an ultraprofitable corporate stasis and an ongoing lie of highly emotive intangibles sold to the general populace in lieu of actual progress.<ref name=\"H\u00e9lice interview\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.revistahelice.com/revista_textos/n_25/Helice.%202019%20Oto%C3%B1o-Invierno%20MARTIAN%20POLITICS%20AND%20THE%20HARD-BOILED%20ANTI-HERO.pdf |title=Martian Politics and the Hard-Boiled Anti-Hero: Richard Morgan\u2019s ''Thin Air'' |author=Sara Mart\u00edn Alegre |year=2018 |journal=Revista H\u00e9lice |volume=4 |issue=11 |pages=84\u201395 |format=PDF |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204065914/https://www.revistahelice.com/revista_textos/n_25/Helice.%202019%20Oto%C3%B1o-Invierno%20MARTIAN%20POLITICS%20AND%20THE%20HARD-BOILED%20ANTI-HERO.pdf |archivedate=4 February 2019 |access-date=3 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n\nA graphic novel titled ''Altered Carbon: Download Blues'', which continues to follow the character Takeshi Kovacs, was released in July 2019.\n\nAn animated feature entitled ''Altered Carbon: Resleeved'' was released in 2020 on Netflix.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Takeshi Kovacs novels===\n* ''[[Altered Carbon]]'' ([[2002 in literature|2002]]) {{ISBN|0-575-07390-X}}\n* ''[[Broken Angels (novel)|Broken Angels]]'' ([[2003 in literature|2003]]) {{ISBN|0-575-07550-3}}\n* ''[[Woken Furies]]'' ([[2005 in literature|2005]]) {{ISBN|0-575-07325-X}}\n* ''[[Altered Carbon: Download Blues]]'' ([[2019 in literature|2019]]) {{ISBN|978-1524109677}}\n\n===''A Land Fit For Heroes''===\n* ''[[The Steel Remains]]'' (2008) {{ISBN|0-575-07792-1}}\n* ''[[The Cold Commands]]'' (2011) {{ISBN|0-575-07793-X}}\n* ''[[The Dark Defiles]]'' (2014) {{ISBN|057508